com.camerontec.catalys.server.breakout

Interface IBreakOutBox

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IComponent, IHasAttributes, IService
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    BreakOutBox

    public interface IBreakOutBox
extends IComponent, IService
    Interface implemented by BreakOutBoxes. A BreakOutBox is a container for messages that have been broken out of the flow of normal processing, but may be broken back in later.

    The normal usage is in a message processor something like this: 

     public class ExampleBreakOutProcessor extends FIXSourceListenerBase {
   private IBreakOutBox breakOutBox;
 
   public boolean openComponent() {
     // ...
 <i>1</i>   <b>setAutoForwarding(false);</b>
 <i>2</i>   <b>breakOutBox = (IBreakOutBox) ServiceManager.getInstance().getService(breakOutBoxServiceName);</b>
 <i>3</i>   <b>breakOutBox.registerMessageProcessor(this);</b>
     // ...
   }
 
   public void onMessageFromFix( MessageEvent event, Message message ) {
 <i>4</i>   <b>if(breakOutBox.breakOutIfRelated(this, message)) {</b>
       <b>return; </b>
     <b>}</b>
     // ...
     if(<i>some condition</i>) {
 <i>5</i>      <b>breakOutBox.breakOut(this, message, "<i>some reason</i>", <i>some reason code</i>);</b>
     } else {
 <i>6</i>      <b>forwardEvent(event);</b>
     }
   }
 }
    1. Turn of auto forwarding (see IFIXMessageProcessor.setAutoForwarding(boolean)), because this message processor is going to decide whether to keep processing a message or put it into the break out box.
    2. Get a break out box from the service manager. This is not always necessary, but it is recommended when the break out box is shared by multiple components (e.g., message processors).
    3. Register this message processor with the breakout box. The breakout box needs this so that it can route messages back to the message processor when it breaks them in.
    4. If the message is related to some other message in the break out box, then the break out box will take care of it and the message processor does not need to process it any further. E.g., if the message is an OrderCancelReplaceRequest for an Order that already in the break out box, then it could be broken out. breakOutIfRelated(IFIXMessageProcessor, IFIXMessage) returns true if it has taken care of the message.
    5. If the message meets some condition (e.g., it has failed a compliance check) then call break it out by calling breakOut(IFIXMessageProcessor, IFIXMessage, String, int) or breakOut(IFIXMessageProcessor, IFIXMessage, List)
    6. Otherwise forward the message. This is necessary because auto forwarding was turned off in step 1.
    Author:
    Hugh Emberson

      • breakIn

        void breakIn(BrokenOutMessageData data,
             boolean retry,
             String user,
             String comment)
      throws Exception
        Insert the broken out message back into the normal flow.
        Parameters:
        data - the message to break in.
        retry - true if the message should be retried through the message processor that broke it out. false if the message should be sent to the next processor after the processor that broke it out.
        user - the user that decided to break the message in. This will be passed to the audit logger.
        comment - a comment that will be passed to the audit logger.

        Exception - TBD
